{"questionId":"19296","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math> is a simple, connected, planar graph with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn></math> vertices and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi></math> edges.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The complement of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math> has <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;edges.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math> is a simple graph with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math>&nbsp;vertices and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi></math> edges.</p>\n<p>Given that both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>H</mi></math> and its complement are planar and connected, find the maximum&nbsp;possible value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>recognises that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;(or equivalent)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>uses&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; and&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>'</mo><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;M1</strong></em></p>\n<p>to form&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>≤</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p>\n<p><br>attempts to solve their quadratic inequality (equality)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mi>v</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>24</mn><mo>≤</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>⇒</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>228</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>≤</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>77</mn><mo>…</mo></math></p>\n<p>the maximum possible value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>10</mn><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>v</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>&nbsp;A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><br>[5 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"19296","referenceCode":"20N.3.AHL.TZ0.Hdm_5d","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"H is a simple graph with v vertices and e edges. Given that both H and its complement are planar and connected, find the maximum possible value of v.","paper":"3","level":"HL","questionNumber":"d","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.14—Graph theory"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}